---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---

<BaseLayout title="Enterprise Knowledge as AI Guardrails — Isra Sunhachawi">
  <article class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-6 py-20">

    <div class="mb-4 animate-fade-in-up">
      <a href={`${base}projects`} class="font-mono text-sm transition-colors" style="color:#7A8BA8;" onmouseover="this.style.color='#10B981'" onmouseout="this.style.color='#7A8BA8'">← projects/</a>
    </div>

    <div class="mb-10 animate-fade-in-up">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-4">
        <span class="font-mono text-xs px-2 py-1 rounded" style="background:rgba(0,145,110,0.1); color:#10B981;">Project 01</span>
        <span class="font-mono text-xs px-2 py-1 rounded" style="background:rgba(224,92,92,0.1); color:#F08080;">In Progress</span>
      </div>
      <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold mb-4" style="color:#E8EDF5;">Enterprise Knowledge as AI Guardrails</h1>
      <div class="h-1 w-16 rounded mb-6" style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, #00916E, #10B981);"></div>
      <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-2">
        {['Claude Code', 'LangGraph', 'n8n', 'CrewAI', 'GitHub Copilot', 'Python', 'Workflows', 'Rules', 'Skills', 'ADR'].map(tag => (
          <span class="skill-tag skill-tag-emerald">{tag}</span>
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="space-y-10">

      <!-- Problem -->
      <div class="glass-card p-6 animate-fade-in-up animate-delay-100">
        <h2 class="font-mono text-sm mb-3" style="color:#10B981;">THE PROBLEM</h2>
        <p style="color:#7A8BA8; line-height:1.9;">
          Every engineering team has unwritten rules — how PRs should be reviewed, how stories get sized, what "done" really means. And written ones that nobody reads: architectural decisions carefully documented in ADRs, violated by the next engineer who never found them. This project asks: what if we could codify that tribal knowledge — spoken and documented alike — as AI-enforced guardrails?
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Three use cases -->
      <div class="animate-fade-in-up animate-delay-200">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-2" style="color:#E8EDF5;">Use Cases: Micro → Meso → Macro</h2>
        <p class="text-sm mb-6" style="color:#7A8BA8;">Arranged by scope — from enforcing a single PR, to planning a sprint, to upholding multi-year architectural commitments.</p>

        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
          <div class="glass-card p-6" style="border-color:rgba(212,160,23,0.2);">
            <div class="font-mono text-xs mb-3" style="color:#D4A017;">USE CASE 1 — MICRO</div>
            <h3 class="font-bold mb-2" style="color:#E8EDF5;">PR Review Guardrails</h3>
            <p class="text-sm mb-4" style="color:#7A8BA8;">
              Encode your team's PR standards — security checks, test coverage expectations, architectural guardrails — as AI-enforced rules that run on every pull request.
            </p>
            <div class="space-y-1 text-xs font-mono" style="color:#7A8BA8;">
              <div><span style="color:#D4A017;">Platform 1:</span> Claude Code rules + hooks</div>
              <div><span style="color:#D4A017;">Platform 2:</span> GitHub Copilot custom instructions</div>
              <div><span style="color:#D4A017;">Platform 3:</span> LangGraph review agent</div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="glass-card p-6" style="border-color:rgba(0,145,110,0.2);">
            <div class="font-mono text-xs mb-3" style="color:#10B981;">USE CASE 2 — MESO</div>
            <h3 class="font-bold mb-2" style="color:#E8EDF5;">Sprint Planning Guardrails</h3>
            <p class="text-sm mb-4" style="color:#7A8BA8;">
              Encode capacity planning norms, definition of ready, estimation heuristics, and sprint health checks as AI workflows — making planning consistently rigorous.
            </p>
            <div class="space-y-1 text-xs font-mono" style="color:#7A8BA8;">
              <div><span style="color:#10B981;">Platform 1:</span> Claude Code skills</div>
              <div><span style="color:#10B981;">Platform 2:</span> n8n automated workflow</div>
              <div><span style="color:#10B981;">Platform 3:</span> CrewAI multi-agent planning</div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="glass-card p-6" style="border-color:rgba(240,128,128,0.2);">
            <div class="font-mono text-xs mb-3" style="color:#F08080;">USE CASE 3 — MACRO</div>
            <h3 class="font-bold mb-2" style="color:#E8EDF5;">Architecture Decision Enforcement</h3>
            <p class="text-sm mb-4" style="color:#7A8BA8;">
              Encode ADRs as AI-enforced constraints that catch violations at three points: before code is written, at PR review, and during design proposals.
            </p>
            <div class="space-y-1 text-xs font-mono" style="color:#7A8BA8;">
              <div><span style="color:#F08080;">Platform 1:</span> Claude Code rules (generation-time, passive)</div>
              <div><span style="color:#F08080;">Platform 2:</span> LangGraph ADR agent (PR-time, automated)</div>
              <div><span style="color:#F08080;">Platform 3:</span> Claude Code skill (design-time, on-demand)</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Key decisions -->
      <div class="animate-fade-in-up animate-delay-300">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4" style="color:#E8EDF5;">Key Decisions</h2>
        <div class="space-y-4">
          {[
            {
              q: 'Why multiple platforms instead of one?',
              a: 'The central thesis is that the knowledge — not the platform — is the durable asset. Showing the same guardrails expressed in Claude Code rules, n8n workflows, and a LangGraph agent proves the concept is portable. It also demonstrates practical breadth across the AI tooling ecosystem.',
            },
            {
              q: 'Why sprint planning as the non-software use case?',
              a: 'Sprint planning is universal, immediately relatable to engineering leaders, and notoriously inconsistent across teams. It shows AI guardrails can govern human processes, not just code — which is the broader enterprise value proposition.',
            },
            {
              q: 'Config-as-code vs. agent workflows — when to use which?',
              a: 'Config-as-code (Claude Code rules, Copilot instructions) is better for synchronous, lightweight guardrails embedded in the developer\'s existing tool. Agent workflows (LangGraph, n8n) are better for async, multi-step processes that aggregate context from multiple sources before making a judgment.',
            },
            {
              q: 'Why enforce ADRs with AI when the real fix is a better engineering culture?',
              a: 'Culture-based solutions require continuous human attention and degrade as teams scale and turn over. AI enforcement doesn\'t replace culture — it institutionalizes the outcomes of past cultural decisions. An ADR represents a hard-won consensus. The guardrail preserves that consensus across personnel changes without requiring every new hire to re-litigate it.',
            },
            {
              q: 'How does the system stay current as ADRs are superseded or deprecated?',
              a: 'ADRs have a lifecycle: proposed, accepted, deprecated, superseded. The Claude Code rules file is updated when an ADR changes. The LangGraph agent draws from the ADR corpus at retrieval time, excluding deprecated entries. This creates a healthy incentive to keep ADRs well-maintained — the system only enforces what\'s current.',
            },
          ].map(({ q, a }) => (
            <div class="glass-card p-5">
              <div class="font-semibold mb-2" style="color:#E8EDF5;">{q}</div>
              <p class="text-sm" style="color:#7A8BA8;">{a}</p>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Status -->
      <div class="glass-card p-6 animate-fade-in-up animate-delay-400" style="border-color:rgba(0,145,110,0.3);">
        <h2 class="font-mono text-sm mb-3" style="color:#10B981;">STATUS</h2>
        <div class="space-y-2">
          {[
            ['done', 'PR review rules defined in Claude Code (.claude/CLAUDE.md + rules)'],
            ['done', 'GitHub Copilot custom instructions baseline created'],
            ['progress', 'LangGraph PR review agent (structured output, tool use)'],
            ['progress', 'Sprint planning skill for Claude Code'],
            ['todo', 'n8n sprint planning workflow'],
            ['todo', 'CrewAI multi-agent sprint planning crew'],
            ['todo', 'ADR library structured as retrieval corpus (JSON/Markdown with status metadata)'],
            ['todo', 'Claude Code rules: generation-time ADR constraints'],
            ['todo', 'LangGraph ADR agent: diff analysis mapped to ADR identifiers'],
            ['todo', 'Claude Code skill: design proposal review against ADR library'],
            ['todo', 'Integration test: one ADR violation caught at all three enforcement points'],
            ['todo', 'Comparative blog post: same guardrail, 5 platforms'],
          ].map(([status, item]) => (
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 text-sm">
              <span style={`color:${status === 'done' ? '#10B981' : status === 'progress' ? '#D4A017' : '#7A8BA8'}`}>
                {status === 'done' ? '✓' : status === 'progress' ? '◐' : '○'}
              </span>
              <span style={`color:${status === 'todo' ? '#7A8BA8' : '#E8EDF5'}`}>{item}</span>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
